<TITLE> Bus strike in south rolls into second day </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 1 (bdnews24.com) - Private bus operators in the south continued to strike Wednesday for a second day, to press home five demands, causing misery to thousands of commuters. No buses were operating on the 33 routes in four districtsKhulna, Bagerhat, Pirojpur and Jhalakathibut BTRC buses were moving on the routes as usual under the tight security. The Combined Owners-Workers United Council called the strike on Tuesday to press demands that include prevention of "irregularities" in the transport sector, banning informal public transport, such as Nasiman and motorcycles, and opposition to BTRC buses. The bus operators also demanded withdrawal of cases against officials of Jhalakathi and Bagerhat Bus-Minibus Owners Association. Nazrul Islam Mantu, president of the Bagerhat Inter-District Bus Owners Association, told bdnews24.com they were continuing their strike on Wednesday as the administration had not contacted them to discuss their demands. "We will continue the strike until the demands are met," he said. BRTC's Khulna depot director Nihar Ranjan Majumder said six buses left the depot Wednesday morning. There were no reports of any obstruction by strikers, he said. Bagerhat police super Awlad Ali Fakir said the police were patrolling for the smooth movement of BRTC buses in the district. Bus operators of Khulna, Pirojpur and Jhalakathi districts also continued striking, but no trouble was reported up to afternoon. bdnews24.c
